This paper deals with reinforcement learning and learning from demonstrations, which are both subfields of machine learning. The paper proposes a new framework for combining these two approaches, which is likely to fall under the category of "Machine Learning" (cs.LG). Additionally, the paper focuses on improving performance in sparse reward environments, which is a common problem in robotics and control systems, suggesting that it could also be classified under "Robotics" (cs.RO) or "Control Systems" (cs.SY). The paper also mentions using image data as input, which could place it under "Computer Vision" (cs.CV). Finally, the paper discusses the use of an actor-critic architecture, which is a common approach in reinforcement learning, suggesting that it could also be classified under "Artificial Intelligence" (cs.AI).
